The defendant Victor Samuel Perez was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Drive or Operate Vehicle w/o Consent [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.23(3).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Original CHANGE OF PLEA/SENTENCING Transcript (29 pages) commencing OCTOBER 27, 2015 received and filed.

Appeal rights given.  Written Explanation of Determinate Sentence, Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief, Pretrial Incarceration Credit and Ineligible Voting Notice & Acknowledgment received and filed.  Copies given to the defendant.

Sentencing proceeds.  State has complied with victim notification.  Statements by counsel and defendant.  COURT ADVISES the defendant he cannot possess firearms, must provide a DNA specimen for testing and cannot vote until his civil rights are restored.  

COURT ORDERS defendant to serve a term in the Wisconsin State Prison system - TOTAL LENGTH OF SENTENCE - 36 months with 106 days credit; INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT - 18 months; EXTENDED SUPERVISION - 18 months.  COURT STAYS the sentence and places the defendant on probation for a period of 3 years.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION:  1) no violations of the criminal law rising to the level of probable cause; 2) obtain GED or HSED; 3) pay mandatory costs, assessments and surcharges or a civil judgment is to be entered against the defendant; 4) seek and maintain employment that doesn't interfere with school; 8) SERVE 60 DAYS at the House of Correction with work release for work for actual employment. 
 
Court advises the defendant any possession or use of any illegally controlled substance or alcohol forfeits the release privileges. 

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION:  1) no violations of criminal law rising to the level of probable cause; 2) seek and maintain employment; 3) obtain GED or HSED.

Court finds defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Substance abuse Program.
